The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 Srinagar, July 20 (PTI): The Amarnath Yatra has been suspended after heavy rain along the two routes to the shrine.           
	Both routes  the traditional 46km trek from Pahalgam in Anantnag district and the 12km one from Baltal in Ganderbal district  have been closed as heavy rain has made the tracks slippery, officials said. The helicopter service to the shrine has also been suspended.                   
	 Dindigul (PTI): A man who allegedly murdered his mother by hitting her on the head with a rolling pin on Sunday is on the run, police said. Pandy, 45, a businessman had suffered heavy losses because of a drink problem and reportedly hit his mother when she refused to lend him money.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): Twenty endangered gaurs, popularly known as Indian bisons, will be shifted from the Kanha tiger reserve to the Bandhavgarh national park in Madhya Pradesh. A wildlife official in Bandhavgarh said gaurs were last seen in the park in 1998, and that this was probably the first translocation of gaurs in the country. Two tigers had earlier been flown from Ranthambore to Sariska in Rajasthan.                  
	 Jhabua (PTI): Eight persons were killed and 55 injured on Sunday when a private bus in which they were travelling overturned at Jobat Naka here, police said. The accident took place in the early hours when the bus was on its way to Indore, they said.                  
	 Kumbakonam (PTI): A 14-year-old boy drowned in the Cauvery near Malaieruppu after a wall along the river bank fell on him while he was taking a bath with a friend. The body was fished out after two hours.                   
	 Madurai (PTI): Civic inspectors seized and destroyed meat worth Rs 10 lakh here on Sunday because it was being sold without the health departments approval. Cases have been registered against the owners.                                                                                                                         
